# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: 1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] The **1788–89 United States House of Representatives elections** were the first U.S.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] House of Representatives elections following the adoption of the Constitution of the United States.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Each state set its own date for its congressional elections, ranging from November 24, 1788, to March 5, 1789, before or after the first session of the 1st United States Congress convened on March 4, 1789.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] They coincided with the election of George Washington as the first president of the United States.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] With the new form of government needing to be operational prior to the completion of the first national census, Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Constitution set a temporary apportionment of seats.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Among the original 13 states, 11 of them ratified the Constitution and elected 59 total representatives.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] North Carolina and Rhode Island did not ratify the Constitution until after the 1st Congress began, and consequently did not elect their representatives until 1790.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Actual political parties did not yet exist, but new members of Congress were informally categorized as either "pro-Administration" (i.e., pro-Washington and pro-Hamilton) or "anti-Administration".
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] The first session of the first House of Representatives came to order in Federal Hall, New York City on March 4, 1789, with only thirteen members present.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] The requisite quorum (thirty members out of fifty-nine) was not present until April 1, 1789.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] The first order of business was the election of a Speaker of the House.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] On the first ballot, Frederick Muhlenberg was elected Speaker by a majority of votes.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] The business of the first session was largely devoted to legislative procedure rather than policy.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Article I, Section 2, Clause 3 of the U.S.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Constitution set a temporary congressional apportionment until the first national census was completed in 1790.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] In the 18th and much of the 19th century, each state set its own date for elections.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] In many years, elections were even held after the legal start of the Congress, although typically before the start of the first session.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] In the elections for the 1st Congress, five states held elections in 1788, electing a total of 29 Representatives, and six held elections in 1789, electing a total of 30 Representatives.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Six seats were filled late because North Carolina and Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] One pro-Administration representative resigned and the seat remained open at the end of the Congress.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] This was the first special election to the United States House of Representatives.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Under the law at the time, each voter cast two votes for representative, at least one of whom had to be from a different county.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Georgia had a mixed at-large/district system for the 1st Congress.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Representatives were elected at-large, but for three district-based seats.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Maryland had a mixed district/at-large system similar to Georgia's.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Massachusetts required a majority vote, necessitating additional votes if no one won a majority.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] This was necessary in 4 of the districts.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] — **The Documentary History of the First Federal Elections: 1788-1790*.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] New Hampshire law required a winning candidate to receive votes from a majority of voters (16.7% of votes).
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] No candidate won such a majority on the first ballot, so a second ballot was held February 2, 1789.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] The election of all four representatives was contested, but the records that explained the precise grounds on which the election was contested have been lost due to the burning of Washington in the War of 1812.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] It is known to have related to questions of regularity and procedure.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] All four representatives' elections were ruled valid.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] New York held elections to the 1st Congress on March 3 and 4, 1789.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] They are retroactively numbered in this section.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] North Carolina ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Pennsylvania held elections to the 1st Congress on November 26, 1788.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] For this first election (and again in 1792 election for the 3rd Congress), Pennsylvania chose to elect all of its representatives on a single statewide general ticket, an attempt by the pro-Administration-majority legislature to prevent anti-Administration candidates from winning seats.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-1789-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-new-hampshire] Rhode Island ratified the Constitution late and thus elected representatives to the 1st Congress in 1790.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] An election to the United States House of Representatives was held in Pennsylvania on November 26, 1788, for the 1st Congress.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] The United States Constitution was adopted on September 17, 1787, by the Constitutional Convention in Philadelphia, and then ratified by the States.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania's legislature ratified the Constitution on December 12, 1787, by a vote of 46–23.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] On July 8, 1788, the Congress of the Confederation passed a resolution calling the first session of the 1st United States Congress for March 4, 1789, to convene at New York City and the election of senators and representatives in the meanwhile by the States.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Pennsylvania's legislature scheduled the election for November 26, 1788, and provided for it to be held on an at-large basis.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] This was an attempt by the Federalist-dominated legislature to prevent anti-Federalist Representatives from being elected in frontier districts.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] Both parties submitted tickets with 8 candidates each.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-election-in-pennsylvania] The large German population in Pennsylvania tended to vote for German candidates, giving the Anti-Federalist Muhlenberg and Hiester enough votes to gain seats.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The **1788 United States House of Representatives elections in South Carolina** were held on November 24 and 25, 1788 to select five Representatives for two-year terms from the state of South Carolina.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] The elections resulted in two candidates in support of Washington's administration and three candidates opposed to his policies.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Smith defeated two candidates in the first election of the 1st congressional district, known as the Charleston District.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Aedanus Burke defeated Robert Barnwell in the first election of the 2nd congressional district, known as the Beaufort-Orangeburg District.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Daniel Huger won the first election of the 3rd congressional district, known as the Georgetown-Cheraw District.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Thomas Sumter won the first election of the 4th congressional district, known as the Camden District.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1788-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections-in-south-carolina] Thomas Tudor Tucker won the first election of the 5th congressional district, known as the Ninety-Six District.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The **1794–95 United States House of Representatives elections** were held on various dates in various states between August 25, 1794 (New Hampshire), and September 5, 1795 (Kentucky).
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Each state set its own date for its elections to the House of Representatives before the first session of the 4th United States Congress convened on December 7, 1795.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] They were held during President George Washington's second term.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections were held for all 105 seats, representing 15 states.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In the first election for the House of Representatives with organized political parties, the Democratic-Republican Party, which opposed the incumbent Washington Administration, defeated the pro-administration Federalist Party.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The outgoing speaker, Frederick Muhlenberg, had supported the pro-administration forces during his first two terms, but was elected by a coalition made up mainly of anti-administration members in 1793, and by 1795 he was seen as more favorable to the Democratic-Republicans.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Despite the Democratic-Republican majority, however, Muhlenberg was not re-elected, and was succeeded by Federalist Jonathan Dayton.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] During this period, each state fixed its own date for a congressional general election.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Elections took place both in the even-numbered year before and in the odd-numbered year when a Congress convened.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] In some states, the congressional delegation was not elected until after the legal start of the Congress (on the 4th day of March in the odd-numbered year).
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] There were special and late elections to the 3rd and 4th Congresses in 1794 and 1795.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Only two candidates are recorded for Delaware's congressional election in 1794, suggesting that the voting procedure in place for the first three Congresses for two candidates had been changed.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Massachusetts redistricted between the 3rd and 4th Congress, dividing itself into 14 districts.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The 12th-14th districts were in the District of Maine (the modern State of Maine).
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Additional ballots were required in five districts due to the majority requirement not being met on the first ballot.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Under New Hampshire's electoral laws, a majority of voters (12.5% of votes) was required for election.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Only three candidates achieved a majority, and so a run-off election was held for the fourth seat.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] New York's districts were not numbered at the time, but were later numbered retroactively.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania once again divided itself into districts instead of electing representatives at-large, as it had for the 3rd Congress.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] The state divided intself into 12 districts, one of which (the 4th) had two seats.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Pennsylvania would continue to use one or more plural districts until 1842.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Electoral data are only available for the 1st and 5th district of South Carolina's 6 districts at the time of the elections of 1794.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Representative-elect Barnwell of the 2nd district declined to serve.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] A special election was held to fill the resulting vacancy, electing Wade Hampton (Democratic-Republican).
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Vermont law required a majority for election to Congress, with a second election to be held if the first did not return a majority.
[src:1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections/1794-95-united-states-house-of-representatives-elections] Run-off elections were required in both districts.
